Fig. 1
a shows that uniform NC QDs with sizes of ∼8nm were formed by hydrothermal synthesis [15] at 180°C for 12h. The inset of Fig. 1a shows lattice fringes with a spacing of 0.21nm corresponding well with the graphite (100) planes. Fig. 1d shows the X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns of the NC QDs, the as-prepared Ni2P nanoparticles and the NC QDs/Ni2P composite. The three prominent diffraction peaks at 2θ=40.7°, 44.6°, 47.4°, and 54.2° in the as-prepared Ni2P nanoparticles and the NC QDs/Ni2P composite are in good agreement with the (111), (201), (210) and (300) diffractions of hexagonal Ni2P (JCPDS file #01-074-1385) [7]. The as-synthesized Ni2P nanoparticles were agglomerated, however, as shown in Fig. 1b. By combining the Ni2P nanoparticles with a dispersion of NC QDs into a hybrid structure, the agglomeration of Ni2P nanoparticles was suppressed, as shown in Fig. 1c. The simultaneous presence of lattice fringes from the (211) facets of Ni2P and the (100) facet of C QDs (0.221nm and 0.21nm respectively) in the HRTEM image of a typical composite particle (Fig. S1, ESI†) confirms the particle’s heterogeneous structure. There was an ultrathin amorphous layer between the Ni2P nanoparticle core and the satellite NC QDs. This amorphous layer indicates that the Ni2P surface was partially oxidized, as has been found before [6,12]. The resulting elemental maps (Fig. 2
) confirm the uniform distribution of NC QDs on the Ni2P nanoparticle surface.
